  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a very strong and widely accepted consensus that money laundering is against the law. It is illegal in virtually every country in the world, and numerous international treaties and organizations are dedicated to combating it.\n\nHere's why the consensus is so strong:\n\n*   **International Legal Framework:** The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is the global standard-setting body for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Its recommendations are followed by most countries. There are also several United Nations conventions that criminalize money laundering.\n\n*   **National Laws:** Almost all countries have laws prohibiting money laundering. These laws typically criminalize the concealment of the origins of illegally obtained money.\n\n*   **Moral and Ethical Considerations:** Money laundering facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, human trafficking, corruption, and fraud. By cleaning illicit funds, it allows criminals to profit from their harmful activities. It also undermines the integrity of financial systems and can destabilize economies.\n\n*   **Impact on Society:** The proceeds of crime used for money laundering often fund further criminal activities, causing significant harm to society.\n\n*   **Law Enforcement Efforts:** Law enforcement agencies around the world actively investigate and prosecute money laundering offenses.\n\nWhile there may be some debate on the *specific* details of money laundering laws (e.g., thresholds for reporting, types of predicate offenses), there is virtually no argument that the act of disguising illegally obtained money to make it appear legitimate is illegal and harmful.\n\nTherefore, it's safe to say that there is a global consensus that money laundering is against the law.\n",
